Let me give you a solid mental model for Podman hooks.Here's a solid mental model for Podman hooks — what they are, how they work, and where they live in the container lifecycle.
What hooks are
A hook is an external executable that Podman calls at specific points in a container's lifecycle. It receives the container's OCI runtime state via stdin as JSON, and can read or modify the container's config before it starts. For NVIDIA use, hooks are how nvidia-container-toolkit injects GPU device mounts into the container automatically.
Let me diagram the full picture:## The key files and their roles
Hook definition — a JSON file in one of these dirs (Podman checks both):
/etc/containers/oci/hooks.d/       ← system-wide
~/.config/containers/oci/hooks.d/  ← user-level (rootless)
A hook JSON looks like this:
{
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "hook": {
    "path": "/usr/bin/nvidia-container-runtime-hook",
    "args": ["nvidia-container-runtime-hook", "prestart"],
    "env": []
  },
  "when": {
    "always": false,
    "annotations": {
      "^run.oci.hooks.nvidia$": ".*"
    },
    "hasBindMounts": false
  },
  "stages": ["prestart"]
}
The when block is the trigger condition — the hook only fires if the container matches. Conditions are OR'd together:
when field	Meaning
"always": true	Fire for every container
"annotations"	Regex match on container annotations
"commands"	Regex match on the container's entrypoint
"hasBindMounts": true	Only if container has bind mounts
The hook binary itself receives the OCI state JSON on stdin:
{
  "ociVersion": "1.0.0",
  "id": "abc123",
  "status": "created",
  "pid": 12345,
  "bundle": "/run/containers/storage/overlay-containers/abc123/userdata"
}
The bundle path is the key — it points to the container's config.json where env vars, mounts, and capabilities live. Your hook script reads this path and modifies config.json before the container process starts.
The NVIDIA-specific chain
/etc/nvidia-container-runtime/config.toml    ← controls what the hook does
/etc/cdi/nvidia.yaml                         ← CDI spec (device descriptions)
/usr/share/containers/oci/hooks.d/oci-nvidia-hook.json  ← hook definition
/usr/bin/nvidia-container-runtime-hook       ← the actual binary
When you run podman run --device nvidia.com/gpu=all, Podman:
1. Reads the hook JSON, sees stages: ["prestart"]
2. At prestart stage, calls nvidia-container-runtime-hook prestart with the OCI state on stdin
3. That binary reads config.toml, finds your disable-require flag, reads the CDI spec
4. Injects /dev/nvidia0, /dev/nvidiactl, libcuda.so, libnvidia-ml.so as mounts into config.json
5. Container process launches with GPU access already wired in
Debugging hooks
# See which hooks are registered
ls -la /etc/containers/oci/hooks.d/
ls -la /usr/share/containers/oci/hooks.d/

# Validate a hook JSON
podman run --rm --hooks-dir /etc/containers/oci/hooks.d/ \
  --log-level=debug hello-world 2>&1 | grep -i hook

# Watch what the hook binary gets on stdin (wrap it)
cat > /tmp/hook-debug.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
STATE=$(cat)
echo "[HOOK] $(date) stage=$1 state=$STATE" >> /tmp/hook-debug.log
echo "$STATE" | /usr/bin/nvidia-container-runtime-hook "$@"
EOF
chmod +x /tmp/hook-debug.sh

# Check what config.toml is actually doing
nvidia-container-cli info   # shows what the CLI layer sees
nvidia-container-cli list   # lists what it would mount

# Manually simulate what the hook does
echo '{"ociVersion":"1.0.0","id":"test","status":"created","bundle":"/tmp/test-bundle"}' \
  | /usr/bin/nvidia-container-runtime-hook prestart
The disable-require flag — what it actually does
In config.toml, disable-require = true tells the hook to skip validating the CUDA_VERSION and DRIVER_VERSION requirements baked into the container image's labels. Specifically it skips this check:
io.nvidia.cuda.requires.cuda = "cuda>=12.0 driver>=570"
Without disable-require, the hook reads those labels from the container image, compares against the host driver version (nvidia-smi → 535), and exits non-zero before injecting anything — so the container never gets GPU access at all. With disable-require = true, it skips that check and injects unconditionally.
That's the layer you're working with — it's purely a version gate in userspace, not a kernel check. The actual question for your DS8 pipeline is which runtime calls then hit the kernel ABI and fail vs which ones happen entirely in CUDA userspace with your 535 driver.



Good question — rootless Podman has its own hooks directory that you do own.
User-level hooks directory
# This is yours — no sudo needed
mkdir -p ~/.config/containers/oci/hooks.d/

# Verify Podman sees it
podman info | grep -i hook
Podman automatically checks both the system dir and your user dir, so hooks you place here fire just like system hooks.
But there's a catch — rootless + NVIDIA
If you're running rootless Podman, the NVIDIA hook binary itself (nvidia-container-runtime-hook) may need root to access /dev/nvidia*. Check:
# Does the hook binary exist and is it executable by you?
ls -la /usr/bin/nvidia-container-runtime-hook
# or
which nvidia-container-runtime-hook

# Can you run nvidia-container-cli as your user?
nvidia-container-cli info
If nvidia-container-cli info works as your user, you're fine. If it errors, you have two paths:

Path 1 — Use CDI instead of hooks (recommended for rootless)
CDI (Container Device Interface) is Podman's newer mechanism that doesn't need hooks at all — devices are specified declaratively and Podman handles injection itself:
# Check if CDI spec already exists
ls /etc/cdi/
ls ~/.config/cdi/     # user-level CDI specs live here

# If system CDI spec exists, just use it directly
podman run --device nvidia.com/gpu=all ...

# If not, generate it to your user dir (no sudo)
mkdir -p ~/.config/cdi
nvidia-ctk cdi generate --output=~/.config/cdi/nvidia.yaml
Then run with:
podman run --device nvidia.com/gpu=all \
  -e NVIDIA_REQUIRE_CUDA="cuda>=11.0 driver>=520" \
  nvcr.io/nvidia/deepstream:8.0-triton-multiarch \
  nvidia-smi

Path 2 — Write hook to your user dir
If CDI isn't available, drop the hook JSON in your user dir:
mkdir -p ~/.config/containers/oci/hooks.d/

cat > ~/.config/containers/oci/hooks.d/nvidia-ds8.json << 'EOF'
{
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "hook": {
    "path": "/usr/bin/nvidia-container-runtime-hook",
    "args": ["nvidia-container-runtime-hook", "prestart"],
    "env": []
  },
  "when": {
    "always": true
  },
  "stages": ["prestart"]
}
EOF
And control the behaviour via env vars at runtime instead of touching config.toml:
podman run --device nvidia.com/gpu=all \
  -e NVIDIA_DISABLE_REQUIRE=1 \
  -e NVIDIA_REQUIRE_CUDA="cuda>=11.0 driver>=520" \
  -e NVIDIA_DRIVER_CAPABILITIES=all \
  -e NVIDIA_VISIBLE_DEVICES=all \
  nvcr.io/nvidia/deepstream:8.0-triton-multiarch \
  nvidia-smi
NVIDIA_DISABLE_REQUIRE=1 is the env var equivalent of disable-require = true in config.toml — it tells the hook binary to skip driver version validation without needing to touch any system config file.

